  Role of Supervision in a Changing Banking Landscape”  Ladies and
  gentlemen, colleagues and friends,  Thank you for the opportunity to
  speak today about a topic that is central to the stability of our
  financial systems: banking supervision. In an era of rapid change —
  from technological innovation to shifting economic conditions and
  the intensifying reality of climate-related risks — the role of
  supervisors is more important than ever. Our objective is simple in
  statement and complex in delivery: to safeguard financial stability
  while enabling banks to support the economy.  Let me highlight three
  core principles that guide effective supervision: forward-looking
  vigilance, proportionality, and cooperation.  First, forward-looking
  vigilance. Supervision must anticipate risks, not merely react to
  them. That means using stress testing, scenario analysis, and
  horizon-scanning to identify vulnerabilities before they
  crystallise. Stress tests remain a key tool to assess banks’
  resilience to macroeconomic shocks, but we complement them with
  targeted thematic reviews — for example on credit underwriting,
  operational resilience, or exposures to climate-related transition
  risk. A forward-looking approach also means expecting banks to have
  robust recovery plans and to maintain capital and liquidity buffers
  sufficient to absorb plausible shocks.  Second, proportionality.
  Banks differ in size, complexity and systemic footprint. Supervisory
  requirements must be proportionate so they are effective without
  unduly constraining the ability of smaller or less complex
  institutions to serve households and businesses. Proportionality
  does not imply lower standards of safety but tailored supervisory
  intensity, calibrated expectations, and an emphasis on material
  risks.  Third, cooperation. Financial markets are interconnected and
  cross-border banking remains integral to the European economy.
  Effective supervision requires close cooperation among national
  authorities, central banks, and European-level bodies. Information
  sharing, joint supervisory colleges, and coordinated crisis
  management frameworks are essential to address cross-border risks
  and to ensure a level playing field.  Against these guiding
  principles, let me outline supervisory priorities that I believe
  warrant our attention today:  - Capital and liquidity resilience:
  Maintaining strong capital and liquidity positions remains the
  bedrock of bank resilience. Supervisors will continue to assess
  banks’ capital adequacy, internal capital planning and their ability
  to withstand stress scenarios.  - Governance and risk culture:
  Effective governance, clear accountability and a strong risk culture
  are crucial. Supervisors expect boards and management to set the
  right tone, to ensure robust internal controls, and to embed risk
  management in strategic decision-making.  - Credit risk and asset
  quality: The economic cycle, sectoral stresses and shifting asset
  valuations call for vigilant credit risk monitoring. We will pay
  particular attention to underwriting standards, concentration risks
  and early signs of loan deterioration.  - Operational resilience and
  cyber risk: As banks digitise services and rely on third-party
  providers, operational risk and cyber threats are rising priorities.
  Supervisors will assess incident preparedness, continuity planning
  and third-party risk management.  - Climate and environmental risks:
  Supervisors increasingly require banks to identify, measure and
  manage climate-related physical and transition risks. This involves
  integrating climate scenario analysis into risk assessments and
  ensuring adequate governance and disclosure.  - Digital
  transformation and model risk: Fintech innovations present both
  opportunities and risks. Supervisors must balance fostering
  innovation with ensuring sound model governance, data quality and
  explainability when advanced analytics are used in decision-making.
  - Anti-money laundering and financial crime: Effective AML/CFT
  frameworks are vital to safeguard integrity. Supervisory
  coordination with relevant authorities is necessary to ensure robust
  compliance and enforcement.  How supervisors approach these
  priorities matters. We rely on a mix of tools: risk-based
  supervision, on- and off-site assessments, targeted inspections,
  stress tests, supervisory dialogues and clear supervisory
  expectations. Transparency and predictability in supervisory
  communications are also important — institutions need clarity on
  expectations so they can plan and invest accordingly.  Looking
  ahead, there are a few developments that will shape supervision in
  the years to come. Digital assets and new payment infrastructures
  require careful monitoring and appropriate regulatory responses.
  Climate risk will become progressively embedded in supervisory
  frameworks, including through enhanced disclosures and scenario-
  based testing. And the drive for better data and analytics will
  transform supervisory capabilities, enabling more timely risk
  detection — while also demanding rigorous model validation and
  explainability.  In closing, let me underscore the shared
  responsibility that underpins our work. Banks have a fundamental
  role in supporting households and businesses; supervisors’ role is
  to ensure that they do so safely and sustainably. This requires
  constructive dialogue between supervisors and banks, a commitment to
  high governance and risk standards from institutions, and continued
  cooperation across jurisdictions and authorities.  By combining
  forward-looking vigilance, proportionate supervision and strong
  cooperation, we can help build a banking system that is resilient,
  trustworthy and able to support sustainable economic growth.  Thank
  you. I look forward to your questions.  Notes for delivery and Q&A -
  Target length: about 10–15 minutes for the speech, followed by a
  brief Q&A. - Q&A prompts: be prepared to discuss stress-testing
  priorities, how supervisors assess climate risk, approaches to cyber
  resilience, and how proportionality is applied across different bank
  sizes. - If asked for institutional or policy positions, ensure you
  have the necessary authorisation before presenting them. Refer media
  enquiries to the communications team.
