Question: I'm approaching the end of my ECB contract and have been notified that
  a cooling-off period applies, which prevents me from taking up the
  new role I had lined up. What financial support is available during
  that period?
Example answer: Certain staff intending to engage in a new occupational activity after
  the end of their ECB employment must refrain, for a specified
  cooling-off period, from any activity that could conflict with the
  ECB's interests. Staff who are prohibited as a result of that
  cooling-off period from undertaking a specific activity and who
  cannot find a suitable alternative and are consequently unemployed
  are entitled, for the duration of the prohibition, to a special
  monthly allowance of 80% of the last basic salary for the first year
  and 60% for the year thereafter, household and child allowances,
  continued cover under the ECB health, long-term care and accident
  insurance (subject to contributions), an education allowance capped
  at EUR 393 per month (or EUR 764 for certified imperative
  educational needs), and accrual of pensionable service. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, pages 3, 18–19)
Predicted answer: If the cooling-off period prevents you from taking up the new role and
  you are therefore unemployed, Article 36a provides that, under the
  conditions in the Staff Rules, you are entitled to benefits for the
  duration of the prohibition and while you remain unemployed (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, p.18; ECB Staff Rules, p.9).  Those
  benefits include: - A monthly unemployment allowance: 60% of your
  last basic salary for six months; then 30% of your last basic salary
  for the subsequent six months, with possible additional months
  related to years of service and age (ECB Conditions of Employment,
  p.17).   - Household and child allowances (ECB Conditions of
  Employment, p.17).   - Continued cover under the ECB health
  insurance, long-term care insurance and accident insurance schemes,
  subject to payment of the relevant contributions (ECB Conditions of
  Employment, p.17).   - An education allowance in accordance with
  Article 19, limited to reimbursement of a maximum of EUR 393 per
  month (increased to a maximum of EUR 764 for children with
  certified, imperative educational needs); payable only until the end
  of the academic year in which you become unemployed (ECB Conditions
  of Employment, p.17).   - A one-off payment equivalent to one
  month’s salary at Band A, step 1 for each full year of service when
  you provide evidence of registration as unemployed and seeking
  employment; this payment shall be no lower than the equivalent of
  three months’ salary at Band A, step 1 and no higher than the
  equivalent of twelve months’ salary at Band A, step 1 (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, p.18).   - Any benefits of the same nature
  received from other sources must be declared and will be deducted
  from amounts payable under this Article (ECB Conditions of
  Employment, p.18).  These entitlements are provided under the
  conditions set out in the Staff Rules, including the notification
  and cooling-off provisions applicable to different grades and
  situations (ECB Staff Rules, p.9; ECB Staff Rules, p.11).
